# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: battle-hill-farm-forest-park
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2001-wellington-regional-council-election-p01] Elections for the regional councils of New Zealand were held from September to 13 October 2001 as part of that year's nation-wide local elections.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2001-wellington-regional-council-election-p01] 134 regional councillors were elected across all 12 regions.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The **2010 Wellington Region local elections** were part of the 2010 New Zealand local elections, to elect members to sub-national councils and boards.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] These elections covered the Wellington Region council (known as the Greater Wellington Regional Council), eight territorial authority (city and district) councils, three district health boards, and various community boards and licensing trusts.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] As per the Local Electoral Act 2001, all the elections occurred on Saturday 9 October 2010.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The Greater Wellington Regional Council (GWRC) is the regional council covering the whole Wellington Region.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] It represents a population of 478,600 as of the Statistics New Zealand's June 2009 estimate, and consists of thirteen councillors elected from six constituencies (Wellington, Lower Hutt, Porirua-Tawa, Kāpiti Coast, Upper Hutt, Wairarapa) using the First Past The Post voting system.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The Wellington constituency returns five members to the GWRC.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The Porirua-Tawa constituency returns two members to the GWRC.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] One member from the Kapiti constituency was elected to GWRC.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Incumbent Nigel Wilson retained the seat against former Kāpiti Coast District councillor Ann Chapman.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] One member from the Wairarapa constituency was elected to GWRC.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2010-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Former Carterton District Council mayor Gary McPhee won the constituency, defeating incumbent Ian Buchannan.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The **2016** **Greater Wellington Regional Council election** was a local election held from September to 8 October in the Greater Wellington region of New Zealand as part of that year's nation-wide local elections.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Voters elected 12 councillors for the 2016–2019 term of the Greater Wellington Regional Council.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Postal voting and the single transferable vote system were used.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Incumbent councillor Judith Aitken did not seek re-election.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Incumbents Sue Kedgley, Chris Laidlaw and Daran Ponter were re-elected, joined by former Wellington City deputy mayor Ian McKinnon and Roger Blakeley.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Incumbent councillors Ken Laban and Prue Lamason were re-elected, while David Ogden defeated incumbent councillor Sandra Greig.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Incumbent councillors Jenny Brash and Barbra Donaldson were re-elected.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Retiring Kapiti Coast District Council councillor Penny Gaylor was elected, defeating incumbent councillor Nigel Wilson.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Incumbent councillor Paul Swain was elected unopposed.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The Wairarapa constituency was vacant following the death of councillor Gary McPhee in June 2016.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2016-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Retiring South Wairarapa mayor Adrienne Staples was elected.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2019-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The **2019** **Greater Wellington Regional Council election** was a local election held from 20 September until 12 October in the Greater Wellington region of New Zealand as part of that year's nation-wide local elections.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2019-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Voters elected thirteen regional councillors for the 2019–2022 term of the Greater Wellington Regional Council.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2019-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] By July 2019 four councillors had announced that they would not be standing for re-election to the Wellington Regional Council; Sue Kedgley, Chris Laidlaw, Ian McKinnon and Paul Swain.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2019-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The GWRC has been "under fire" for changes to the bus services, particularly in Wellington city.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2019-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Names in bold font identify successful candidates.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The **2022 Greater Wellington Regional Council election** was a local election held from 16 September until 8 October in the Greater Wellington region of New Zealand as part of that year's nation-wide local elections.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Voters elected thirteen regional councillors for the 2022–2025 term of the Greater Wellington Regional Council.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The election was held using the single transferable vote system.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Thirteen councillors were elected across six constituencies.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] All five incumbent councillors stood for re-election.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Roger Blakeley and Glenda Hughes were unsuccessful.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] David Lee, Thomas Nash, and Daran Ponter were re-elected.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] They were joined by Simon Woolfe and Yadana Saw.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2022-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Daran Ponter, a Labour councillor, was elected as chair unopposed.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2025-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The **2025 Greater Wellington Regional Council election** was a local election held from 9 September to 11 October in the Wellington region of New Zealand, as part of that year's regional council elections and other local elections held nation-wide.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2025-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The Greater Wellington Regional Council makes decisions about environmental management, flood protection and land management, the provision of regional parks, public transport planning and funding, and metropolitan water supply for Greater Wellington.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2025-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The council introduced a Māori constituency for this election and, in a referendum on its future held alongside this election, as part of a nation-wide series of referendums, voters elected to keep the Māori constituency.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2025-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] In October 2023, the Greater Wellington Regional Council voted to create a Māori constituency for the 2025 & 2028 elections.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2025-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] In July 2024, the National-led coalition government passed the Local Government (Electoral Legislation and Māori Wards and Māori Constituencies) Amendment Act 2024 which reinstated the requirement that councils must hold a referendum before establishing Māori wards or constituencies.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2025-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The council then voted unanimously in August 2024 to affirm their decision to establish the Māori constituency, thereby triggering a referendum on the constituency to be held alongside the 2025 local elections.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2025-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Te Upoko o te ika a Māui Māori constituency returned one councillor to the regional council.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2025-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] As the only candidate, Makarini was elected unopposed to be the inaugural Te Upoko o te ika a Māui Māori constituency councillor.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2025-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The Kāpiti Coast constituency returned one councillor to the regional council.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2025-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The Porirua-Tawa constituency returned two councillors to the regional council.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2025-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Te Awa Kairangi ki Uta/Upper Hutt constituency returned one councillor to the regional council.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2025-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] As the only candidate, Connelly was re-elected unopposed.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2025-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] Te Awa Kairangi ki Tai/Lower Hutt constituency returned three councillors to the regional council.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2025-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The Pōneke/Wellington constituency returned five councillors to the regional council.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/2025-greater-wellington-regional-council-election] The Wairarapa constituency returned one councillor to the regional council.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The area of the park has seen human interaction for approximately 700 years, with evidence of habitation dating back to early Māori iwi such as Waitaha and Rapuwai during the early periods of Māori habitation in New Zealand.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Following the arrival of Pākehā in the 19th century, the area saw widespread deforestation, farming, and quarrying, significantly modifying the area's environment.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this, the park is one of the most modified landscapes of any of New Zealand's national parks, with management of the park largely focusing on regeneration and restoration of the traditional ecosystem.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was first established in 1942 to commemorate the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's 1642 visit in New Zealand, when he became the first European to sight the islands.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It has since been progressively expanded from its original borders, the most recent of which involved the addition of 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet after a successful crowdfunding campaign.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The coastal area was inhabited for hundreds of years by Māori prior to the arrival of Europeans, with sites throughout the area occupied both seasonally and permanently.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In addition to harvesting food from the local forests, estuaries and waters, locals grew kūmara.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Historical records indicate a pā was established at Auckland Point by Pohea, who travelled there around 1450 from the Whanganui area.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] From the mid-1500s Muaūpoko (formerly known as Ngāi Tara) occupied the area until the early 1600s, when they were ousted by Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri were present when Abel Tasman reached Golden Bay / Mohua in 1642.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was founded in 1942, largely through the efforts of ornithologist and author Pérrine Moncrieff to have land reserved for the purpose.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Moncrieff served on the park board from 1943 to 1974.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was opened on 18 December 1942 to mark the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's visit.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Those in attendance at the opening ceremony at Tarakohe included Charles van der Plas, as personal representative of the Netherlands' Queen, Wilhelmina.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The idea for the park had been under consideration since June 1938.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Crown set aside 15,225 hectares (37,622 acres), comprising 8,900 hectares (21,900 acres) of proposed state forest, 5,809 hectares (14,354 acres) of Crown land and 554 hectares (1,368 acres) of other reserve land for the national park.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Golden Bay Cement Company donated the land where the Abel Tasman Monument and a memorial plaque was sited.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The area's primary historic interest was the visit of Tasman in 1642, D'Urville in 1827, and the New Zealand Company barques *Whitby* and *Will Watch*, and brig *Arrow* in 1841.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The site was also of significant botanical interest.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] By 1946 the park had reached 15,534 hectares (38,386 acres) in area with additional land purchases.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] A further 844 hectares (2,085 acres) at Tōtaranui, formerly owned by William Gibbs, was acquired from J S Campbell in 1949 and added to the park.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] About 6,100 hectares (15,000 acres) have been added since.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2008 an extra 7.9 km2 (790 ha; 3.1 sq mi), including the formerly private land known as Hadfields Clearing, were added to the park.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2016, a further 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet was purchased by New Zealanders in a crowdfunding campaign.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Covering an area of 237 km2 (92 sq mi; 59,000 acres), the park is the smallest of New Zealand's national parks.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It consists of forested, hilly country to the north of the valleys of the Tākaka and Riwaka Rivers, and is bounded to the north by the waters of Golden Bay / Mohua and Tasman Bay.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains some of the islands off the coast including the Tata Islands in Golden Bay / Mohua, and Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island, and Fisherman Island in Tasman Bay.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park does not extend beyond Mean High Water Mark on the adjacent coast.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Between Mean High Water and Mean Low Water Springs, the beaches are gazetted as a Scenic Reserve, covering 7.74 km2 (2.99 sq mi) in total.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Tonga Island Marine Reserve adjoins part of the park.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Monument, though not located in the park, commemorates the first contact between Europeans and Māori and is located near the northern end of the park.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Abel Tasman National Park stands out from most other National parks of New Zealand, given that a large area of it has undergone extensive environmental modification in its history.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Early European settlers burned or cleared much of the forest, only to find that the soil was unsuitable for farming.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] This practise not only destroyed much of the shrubland and forests, but also introduced invasive plants found throughout the modern-day park.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] However, as time progresses, the original ecosystems and forests are slowly returning.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains varied habitats, including coastal forests, sub-alpine bogs, and sand dunes.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this diversity, many different species can be found.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The islands of the park, in particular Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island and Fisherman Island which are the largest, have been disturbed less and have no introduced mammalian predators.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result the islands have species not found elsewhere in the park and there are more restrictions to visitor access.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Though much of the parkland is pasture or covered with shrubs, valley areas contain forests of rātā, mataī, miro and hinau.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Over 70 species of birds have been recorded in the park.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Some of the birds that can frequently be seen are petrels, shags, penguins, gulls, terns, and herons.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Possums, wild pigs, deer, and goats can also be seen in the park.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Coast Track is a popular tramping track that follows the coastline and is one of the Department of Conservation's Great Walks; the Abel Tasman Inland Track is less frequented.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Other walks in the park, such as the Wainui Falls Track are considered "short walks".
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Kayaking, camping and sightseeing are other activities.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Access to the park is usually via the small settlement of Mārahau or Kaiteriteri (by water taxi).
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The nearest large town is Motueka, 20 kilometres (12 mi) to the south.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Dogs (excepting guide dogs) are not allowed in the park.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation administers the National Park.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Scenic Reserve is administered by the Tasman District Council Chief Executive and Department of Conservation's Nelson / Marlborough Conservator.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Activities in adjoining coastal waters are Tasman District Council's responsibility.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] These areas operate under separate regulations.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Interior, consisting of the park areas further inland.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Park plans include ecological surveys, pest control, and protection of heritage areas and caves.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Islands, encompassing all islands within the park, some of which are closed to the public. key priorities include keeping them free of invasive pests, reintroducing native species, and minimizing human impacts.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2012 Project Janszoon, a privately funded trust, was set up to restore the park's ecosystems.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The trust takes its name from Tasman's middle name *Janszoon*.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It is aiming to complete the restoration in time for the 400th anniversary of Tasman's visit and the park's 100th anniversary in 2042.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation and Project Janszoon developed a free virtual visitor centre for downloading to smartphones or tablets.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The application provides information about the Park's history, its flora and fauna, points of interest, weather, walking tracks, and tides.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] This virtual visitor centre is free of charge and can be found through the App Store or Google Play Store.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] The park is a dedicated farm park, administered by Wellington Regional Council.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] Transmission Gully runs through the park.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] The reserve covers a stream valley, between Paekākāriki Hill and Horokiri stream to the west, and hills to the east.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] It includes steep hill slopes of greywacke with limited vegetation.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] The vegetation in the valley includes pukatea (*Laurelia novaezelandiae*), along with some rewarewa (*Knightia excelsa*), tawa (*Beilschmeidia tawa*), and kahikatea (*Dacrycarpus dacrydioides*).
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] The understory includes māhoe (*Melicytus ramiflorus*), kaikomako (*Pennantia corymbosa*), nīkau (*Rhopalostylis sapida*), coprosma, and other small trees and shrubs.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] Battle Hill Farm Forest Park was the site of Battle of Battle Hill in 1846.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] Relations between the Government and local Māori had been souring for many years, due to the New Zealand Company trying to buy large tracts of land for Pākehā settlers.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] It culminated with a clash between about 300 Ngāti Toa, under the leadership of Te Rangihaeata, and British troops.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] Te Rangihaeata was captured and relinquished the land in return for his release.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] He spent the rest of his life in exile at Poroutawhao, north of Levin.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] In 1860 the bush was covered to the Abbott family, who cleared it and farmed it until 1975.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] Members of the family, and two of the three militiamen killed in the battle of 1846, are buried in a graveyard on the site.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] Wellington Regional Council purchased the land for a park in 1987.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] Access routes into the park were changed, during construction of Transmission Gully between 2016 and 2021.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] The council consulted on the future of the park in 2020.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] Later that year, the council announced plans to reduce stock grazing and increase native bush and wetlands in its regional parks.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] However, it excluded Battle Hill Farm Forest Park from the plan, opting to keep it as a dedicated farm park.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] The park contains a working farm near the entrance at Paekākāriki Hill Road and extends over the surrounding hills and into a plantation forest that merges with the Akatarawa Forest.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] It contains several loop walkways, some suitable for mountain biking and horse riding.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] Parts of the park are closed during August for lambing season.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] The park is open to camping and campervans.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] However, there is no powered camping sites or dump stations.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] Wellington Riding for the Disabled, a community group providing horse therapy for people with disabilities, has been operating in the park since 2016.
[src:battle-hill-farm-forest-park/battle-hill-farm-forest-park] The park is a ten minute drive from parts of Porirua.
